@node Objective
@chapter Objective
@cindex objective

@menu
* Rationale::
* Use with Linux STREAMS::
* Use with Linux Fast-STREAMS::
@end menu

The @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package is intended to provide maximum compatibility between
@cite{Linux STREAMS (LiS)} or @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS (LfS)} and other @dfn{STREAMS} implementations on
major UNIX operating systems, for the purpose of porting existing @dfn{STREAMS} modules and drivers from
those operating system to @dfn{Linux}.

Also, the @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package aims to provide compatibility between @cite{Linux
STREAMS (LiS)} and @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} to ease the porting of @dfn{STREAMS} modules and drivers from
@cite{LiS} to @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} with minimal effort.

To meet that objective, @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} aims to support the @dfn{STREAMS} DDI/DKI and
registration functions of the following @dfn{STREAMS} implementations:

@sp 1
@itemize
@item UNIX System V Release 3.2
@item UNIX System V Release 4 MP
@item UNIX System V Release 4.0 MP
@item UNIX System V Release 4.2 MP
@item Mentat Portable Streams (MPS)
@item Linux STREAMS LiS 2.16
@item Linux STREAMS LiS 2.18
@item Linux Fast-STREAMS 0.7a
@item Linux Fast-STREAMS 0.9.2
@item AIX 5L Version 5.1 Portable STREAMS Environment (PSE)
@item HP-UX 11.0i v2 STREAMS/UX
@item OSF/1.2 - Digital UNIX STREAMS
@item UnixWare 7.1.3 (OpenUnix 8) STREAMS
@item Solaris 9/SunOS 5.9 (OpenSolaris) STREAMS
@item Mac OS 9 OpenTransport 1.5r2
@item IRIX 6.5.17 STREAMS
@item SUPER-UX Release 9.2
@item UXP/V V10L10 STREAMS V10
@end itemize

@sp 1
Because it is not necessary to have all of these compatibility modules loaded at a given time, and
to reduce the footprint of the resulting kernel modules, the @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package
implements these compatibility modules as separate demand loadable @dfn{Linux} kernel modules.

The @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package contains compatibility modules that were originally part of
the @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} package.  They have been separated into an package independent from
@cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} for the purpose of provide some of the same capabilities to @cite{Linux
STREAMS (LiS)} in advance of production releases of @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS}.

@page
@node Rationale
@section Rationale
@cindex rationale

The @cite{@value{PACKAGE_TITLE}} package is designed and implemented to be compatible with as many
@cite{SVR 4.2 MP} based implementations of @dfn{STREAMS}a s possible.  This is done for several
reasons:

@enumerate
@item Porting legacy drivers to @dfn{Linux}:

Many legacy @dfn{STREAMS} drivers have been written and developed for @cite{SVR 4.2 MP} or
@dfn{UNIX} systems based on @cite{SVR 4.2 MP}.  Remaining compatible with as many implementations as
possible permits these legacy drivers to be easily ported from their native @dfn{UNIX} variant to
the @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} environment, thus quickly porting these legacy drivers to @dfn{Linux}.

@item Leverage of knowledge base:

Many developers are familiar with one or another of the mainstream @dfn{UNIX} implementations of
@cite{SVR 4.2 MP STREAMS}.  By remaining as compatible as possible with all these implementations
of @dfn{STREAMS} permits knowledge and expertise in the @dfn{UNIX} variant of @dfn{STREAMS} to be
transferred and applied to @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} on @dfn{Linux}.

@item Reverse portability:

Because it is compatible as possible with other @dfn{STREAMS} implementations, @dfn{STREAMS} drivers
and modules developed on @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} can easily be ported to other implementations if
a set of compatibility and portability guidelines are followed.  This allows @dfn{STREAMS} driver and
modules developed on the @dfn{Linux} operating system to be used on branded @dfn{UNIX} systems with
minimal porting and modification.

@item Multiple baselines:

Because the source code developed for @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} can remain quite close to that for
other mainstream @dfn{UNIX} implementations of @cite{SVR 4.2 MP STREAMS}, it is possible to have
multiple baselines for different architectures in the same source code files.  This eases the
maintenance of @dfn{STREAMS} drivers and modules across @cite{Linux Fast-STREAMS} and other
@dfn{UNIX} systems.

@item Standardization:

By being as compatible as possible with many @dfn{STREAMS} implementations as possible, @cite{Linux
Fast-STREAMS} implements an ipso facto standard.  Unfortunately, the @url{http://www.opengroup.org/,
OpenGroup} and @cite{POSIX} have been very lacking in the standardization of internal kernel
interfaces such as @dfn{STREAMS}.  Maximum compatibility moves close to providing a standard for
such interfaces.

@item Licensing and Technology Binding

By implementing an ipso facto standard, independent @dfn{STREAMS} drivers and modules written to the
